revision.text:
[[File:Svetozar Corovic House.jpg|thumb|Svetozar Corovic House]] The house where [[Svetozar Ćorović]] was born has been transformed into a [[writer's home museum]]. The museum is located in [[Mostar]], Bosnia and Herzegovina. Svetozar Ćorović is one of the most important Herzegovina novelists<ref name="www.imdb.com">[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0180620/bio/ IMDB]</ref> who often wrote of life in Herzegovina region and in Mostar, is located at Mostar's 178, Maršala Tita Street, close to the Muyaga Komadina Bridge (or Luka Bridge). It was constructed in 1874 in a somewhat unusual [[Neo-Renaissance]] style.<ref name="www.turizam.mostar.ba">[http://www.turizam.mostar.ba/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=129:kua-svetozara-orovia-&catid=43:muzeji-i-galerije&Itemid=423&lang=en/ City of Mostar]</ref> The building style was also inspired by the Dalmatian architecture.<ref name="www.muzejhercegovine.com">[http://muzejhercegovine.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17&Itemid=32/ Svetozar Corovoc House - In local Language]</ref>
[[Aleksa Šantić]], one of the country’s greatest poets, also lived here during the last years of his life. The building houses a room dedicated to his memory with a library collection containing his precious manuscripts.
The city honors Šantić by holding poetry reading evenings, the Šantićeve večeri poezije, an event much which has taken place every year for the past twenty three years.<ref name="https://web.archive.org/web/20110701024925/http://www.comune.fi.it/mostar/en/live/museumhouse.html">[http://www.comune.fi.it/mostar/en/live/museumhouse.html/ House Museums]</ref>
