'''Joseph Hewahewa Kaimihakulani Heleluhe''' (June 2, 1855 – July 8, 1900) was a member of the Hawaiian nobility who served as a retainer and private secretary of Queen [[Liliuokalani|Liliʻuokalani]], the last monarch of the [[Kingdom of Hawaii]], and accompanied her on her trips to the United States and [[Washington, DC]] from 1896 to 1900 to prevent the American [[annexation of Hawaii]].
{{anchor|Biography|History}}

==Life==

===Early life===
He was born in June 2, 1855, on the [[Hawaii (island)|island of Hawaiʻi]]. English language newspapers claimed he was a native of [[Kau, Hawaii|Kaʻū]] while the ''Ke Aloha Aina'', a [[Hawaiian language]] newspaper, claimed he was born in [[Kapoho, Hawaii|Kapoho]], [[Puna, Hawaii|Puna]].<ref name="Mookuauhau">{{cite news|title=Mookuauhau O Joseph Kaimihakulani Heleluhe|newspaper=Ke Aloha Aina|location=Honolulu|date=July 28, 1900|volume=VI|issue=30|page=1|url=https://nupepa-hawaii.com/2014/01/15/joseph-heleluhe-1900/|accessdate=November 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112091148/https://nupepa-hawaii.com/2014/01/15/joseph-heleluhe-1900/|archive-date=November 12, 2016|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name="Death">{{cite news|title=Death Came On The Way – The Passing of Joseph Heleluhe|newspaper=The Hawaiian Gazette|location=Honolulu|date=July 10, 1900|volume=XXXV|issue=55|page=6|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83025121/1900-07-10/ed-1/seq-6/|access-date=November 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220060946/http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83025121/1900-07-10/ed-1/seq-6/|archive-date=December 20, 2016|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Death Came On The Way – The Passing of Joseph Heleluhe|newspaper=The Pacific Commercial Advertiser|location=Honolulu|date=July 10, 1900|volume=XXXII|issue=5592|page=1|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1900-07-09/ed-1/seq-1/|access-date=November 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170109054001/http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1900-07-09/ed-1/seq-1/|archive-date=January 9, 2017|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Joseph {{sic|Heleuhe|hide=y}} Dead|newspaper=The Maui News|location=Wailuku|date=July 14, 1900|volume=I|issue=22|page=2|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82014689/1900-07-14/ed-1/seq-2/|access-date=November 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220030601/http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82014689/1900-07-14/ed-1/seq-2/|archive-date=December 20, 2016|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Death of Heleluhe|newspaper=The Independent|location=Honolulu|date=July 9, 1900|volume=XI|issue=1554|page=3|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047097/1900-07-09/ed-1/seq-3/|access-date=November 12, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170109085253/http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047097/1900-07-09/ed-1/seq-3/|archive-date=January 9, 2017|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Certificates of Death|newspaper=The Independent|location=Honolulu|date=July 21, 1900|volume=XI|issue=1564|page=1|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047097/1900-07-21/ed-1/seq-1/|access-date=November 12, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170109085424/http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047097/1900-07-21/ed-1/seq-1/|archive-date=January 9, 2017|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Joseph Heleluhe Dead – For Several Years Secretary of Ex-Queen Liliuokalani|newspaper=The Hawaiian Star|location=Honolulu|date=July 9, 1900|volume=VII|issue=2605|page=3|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015415/1900-07-09/ed-1/seq-3/|accessdate=November 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220050148/http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015415/1900-07-09/ed-1/seq-3/|archive-date=December 20, 2016|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref> His parents were Heleluhe and Kanoa. He had four known sisters: Keoki, Kaioewa, Kanoa, and Ana. From his mother Kanoa, he descended from [[Alapainui|Alapaʻinui]] and his son [[Keaweʻōpala]], the kings of the island of Hawaiʻi prior to the accession of [[Kalaniʻōpuʻu]].<ref name="Mookuauhau"/> His father was possibly the same individual as J. H. Heleluhe, who served in the [[Legislature of the Kingdom of Hawaii|legislature of the kingdom]] as a member of the House of Representatives for the district of Puna during the legislative assembly of 1855, 1862, 1864, 1866 and 1867.<ref name="Father">{{harvnb|Hawaii|Lydecker|1918|pages=64, 86, 103, 107, 109}}; {{harvnb|Osorio|2002|pages=109, 118, 138}}; {{cite news|title=House of Representatives|newspaper=The Polynesian|location=Honolulu|date=June 28, 1862|volume=XIX|issue=9|page=2|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015408/1862-06-28/ed-1/seq-2/|accessdate=November 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220050107/http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015408/1862-06-28/ed-1/seq-2/|archive-date=December 20, 2016|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref>

He attended the local schools in the Puna district and later studied at the Hilo Boarding School under American missionary [[David Belden Lyman]]. After finishing his education, he did physical labor in the district of Kaʻū for a time before going to [[Honolulu]] to serve King [[Kalākaua]].<ref name="Mookuauhau"/><ref name="Death"/>

===Service to the Hawaiian monarchy===
After coming to Honolulu, Heleluhe worked as a retainer for the royal family. He served King Kalākaua as an under-secretary. He also worked as a steward for Kalākaua's sister and successor [[Liliuokalani|Liliʻuokalani]], and accompanied her to the leper settlement at [[Kalaupapa]] on [[Molokai]] in 1891. He steadily rose in rank until he was appointed her private secretary in 1896.<ref name="Mookuauhau"/><ref name="Death"/><ref>{{cite news|title=The Queen at Molokai|newspaper=The Daily Bulletin|location=Honolulu|date=April 25, 1891|volume=XV|issue=100|page=2|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015408/1862-06-28/ed-1/seq-2/|accessdate=November 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220050107/http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015408/1862-06-28/ed-1/seq-2/|archive-date=December 20, 2016|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 1892. Heleluhe was nominated as a [[National Reform Party (Hawaii)|National Reform Party]] candidate for the House of Representatives for Oʻahu's first ward. He lost this election.<ref>{{harvnb|Kuykendall|1967|page=517}}; {{cite news|title=List Of Candidates|newspaper=The Pacific Commercial Advertiser|location=Honolulu|date=February 3, 1892|volume=|issue=|page=4|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1892-02-03/ed-1/seq-4/|access-date=July 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171125080827/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1892-02-03/ed-1/seq-4/|archive-date=November 25, 2017|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Legislature Of 1892|newspaper=The Pacific Commercial Advertiser|location=Honolulu|date=February 26, 1892|volume=|issue=|page=1|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1892-02-26/ed-1/seq-1/|access-date=July 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171125080830/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1892-02-26/ed-1/seq-1/|archive-date=November 25, 2017|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref> After the [[overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawaii|overthrow of the monarchy]] in 1893, Heleluhe and his wife Wakeke Ululani remained loyal to the royalist cause and supported the deposed Queen Liliʻuokalani.{{sfn|Bonura|Witmer|2013|page=126}} Following the outbreak of the unsuccessful [[1895 Counter-revolution in Hawaii|1895 Counter-Revolution]], Heleluhe was arrested, held as a political prisoner, and temporarily imprisoned by forces loyal to the [[Republic of Hawaii]] in order for him to "disclose the queen's treachery."<ref name="Death"/><ref name=review>{{harvnb|Mellen|1958|page=311}}; {{harvnb|Allen|1982|page=330}}</ref> Queen Liliʻuokalani, who was also imprisoned in the former [[ʻIolani Palace]], described the ordeal Heleluhe had to endure in her 1898 memoir ''[[Hawaii's Story by Hawaii's Queen]]'':

<blockquote>Mr. Heleluhe was taken by the government officers, stripped of all clothing, placed in a dark cell without light, food, air, or water, and was kept there for hours in hopes that the discomfort of his position would induce him to disclose something of my affairs. After this was found to be fruitless, he was imprisoned for about six weeks; when, finding their efforts in vain, his tormentors released him. No charge was ever brought against him in any way, which is true of about two hundred persons who were similarly confined.{{sfn|Liliuokalani|1898|pages=[https://books.google.com.hk/books?id=NLM4DQAAQBAJ&pg=PT185 270–271]}}<ref name=review/></blockquote>

[[File:Liliuokalani with her lady-in-waiting and secretary.jpg|thumb|right|The Queen with Joseph Heleluhe and her lady-in-waiting Elizabeth Kia Nahaolelua, c. 1896–97]]

Between 1896 and 1900, Heleluhe accompanied Queen Liliʻuokalani on her many trips abroad to the United States and [[Washington, DC]] to campaign against the American [[annexation of Hawaii]] and then assisted her in her attempts to reclaim the crown land after 1898. Initially, Elizabeth Kia Nahaolelua was chosen to be her lady-in-waiting but after the trips were extended, Heleluhe's wife Wakeke replaced her in the royal party as lady-in-waiting to the queen.<ref name="Death"/><ref>{{harvnb|Mellen|1958|page=331}}: {{harvnb|Allen|1982|pages=355–356, 359}}: {{harvnb|Silva|2004|page=193}}; {{cite news|title=E Huli Hoi Mai Ana|newspaper=Ka Makaainana|location=Honolulu|date=May 3, 1897|volume=VII|issue=18|page=8|url=https://nupepa-hawaii.com/2014/01/14/wakeke-heleluhe-to-take-the-place-of-kia-kahele-nahaolelua-1897/|accessdate=November 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112150045/https://nupepa-hawaii.com/2014/01/14/wakeke-heleluhe-to-take-the-place-of-kia-kahele-nahaolelua-1897/|archive-date=November 12, 2016|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Mrs. Heleluhe No Amerika|newspaper=Ke Aloha Aina|location=Honolulu|date=May 1, 1897|volume=III|issue=18|page=6|url=https://nupepa-hawaii.com/2014/01/26/more-on-mrs-heleluhe-going-to-take-the-place-of-kahele-nahaolelua-and-name-variations-1897/|accessdate=November 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112145735/https://nupepa-hawaii.com/2014/01/26/more-on-mrs-heleluhe-going-to-take-the-place-of-kahele-nahaolelua-and-name-variations-1897/|archive-date=November 12, 2016|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref> From 1897 to 1898, Heleluke was also actively involved in rallying Hawaiians in signing the [[Kūʻē Petitions]] and petitioning against annexation. In 1897, he wrote to US President William McKinley and Secretary of State John Sherman with the petitions collected by Hui Aloha ʻĀina (Hawaiian Patriotic League) and Hui Kālaiʻāina.<ref>{{cite web|title=Joseph Heleluhe, June 1897 to John Sherman, U.S. Secretary of State|url=http://libweb.hawaii.edu/digicoll/annexation/protest/liliu7.php|accessdate=November 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112144044/http://libweb.hawaii.edu/digicoll/annexation/protest/liliu7.php|archive-date=November 12, 2016|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite web|title=Joseph Heleluhe, July 1897 to William McKinley, U.S. President|url=http://libweb.hawaii.edu/digicoll/annexation/protest/liliu7.php|accessdate=November 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112144044/http://libweb.hawaii.edu/digicoll/annexation/protest/liliu7.php|archive-date=November 12, 2016|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref>

Following Liliʻuokalani's return to Hawaii in 1900, the 45-year-old Heleluhe succumbed to [[tuberculosis]], on July 8, 1900. When it became evident his death was near, his final request was to die at [[Washington Place]]. Although he expired before arrival at the queen's residence, his funeral was held there. He was buried at the [[Kawaiahaʻo Church]] cemetery.<ref name="Death"/>

==Family==
[[File:Prince Jack Heleluhe, 1914.jpg|thumb|right|"Prince" Jack Heleluhe, 1914]]

Heleluhe married Wakeke Ululani Heleluhe, from [[Maui]], who served as a lady-in-waiting to Queen Liliʻuokalani. They had two children: Jack Heleluhe and Myra Kailipanio Heleluhe Iona.<ref name="Wakeke"/> Jack, also known as "Prince Jack Heleluhe", worked as a musician and member of the [[Royal Hawaiian Band]]; he became one of the first musicians to play [[Hawaiian music]] in the United States and was featured on N. B. Bailey's 1914 book ''A Practical Method for Self Instruction on the Ukulele and Banjo Ukulele''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukediner.ukulele.org/heleluhe.html|title=Prince Jack Heleluhe—a "kanaka" of the Hawaiian musical scene and road-worthy veteran of the mainland|accessdate=November 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514024059/http://ukediner.ukulele.org/heleluhe.html|archive-date=May 14, 2008|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Myra became a protège of the queen at a young age and later served as an associate of Princess [[Elizabeth Kahanu Kalanianaʻole]] and Prince [[Jonah Kūhiō Kalanianaʻole]].{{sfn|Iaukea|2011|pages=70, 102, 116, 123, 126}}

In 1906, Wakeke lost favor with the queen after an attempt to discredit [[Lydia Kaʻonohiponiponiokalani Aholo]], the queen's ''[[hānai]]'' daughter, backfired, and she was evicted from the houses she occupied at Washington Place and the queen's residence in [[Waikiki]] by the queen and her financial agent [[Joseph O. Carter]]. The reasons given for the queen's anger was Wakeke's "disloyalty to me and dishonesty"; she had lied to Aholo that the queen never wished to see her again.{{sfn|Bonura|Witmer|2013|pages=123–126}} She may have later reconciled with the queen because Wakeke and Onalaa were listed as two of her old retainers at the deathbed of the queen. She, her daughter Myra and [[Lahilahi Webb]] stood vigil by Liliʻuokalani's casket while her body laid in the [[Royal Mausoleum of Hawaii|Royal Mausoleum]] prior to her final interment in the vault of the Kalākaua Crypt.<ref>{{cite news|title=Death Comes to Hawaii's Queen in Calm of Sabbath Morning|newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|location=Honolulu|date=November 12, 1917|volume=|issue=|page=2|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82014682/1917-11-12/ed-1/seq-2/|accessdate=September 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108164527/http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82014682/1917-11-12/ed-1/seq-2/|archive-date=November 8, 2017|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}' {{cite news|title=Body of Queen Is Sealed Away In Royal Crypt|newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|location=Honolulu|date=November 26, 1917|volume=|issue=|page=4|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82014682/1917-11-26/ed-1/seq-4/|accessdate=November 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220030556/http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82014682/1917-11-26/ed-1/seq-4/|archive-date=December 20, 2016|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref>
Wakeke died at her Honolulu home, on November 21, 1921.<ref name="Wakeke">{{cite news|title=Make Ka Hoahele O Ka Moi Wahine Liliu|newspaper=Ka Nupepa Kuokoa|location=Honolulu|date=November 25, 1921|volume=LIX|issue=47|page=4|url=https://nupepa-hawaii.com/2014/01/14/wakeke-ululani-heleluhe-passes-away-1921/|accessdate=November 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112151117/https://nupepa-hawaii.com/2014/01/14/wakeke-ululani-heleluhe-passes-away-1921/|archive-date=November 12, 2016|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Former Companion of Queen Dies in Her Honolulu Home|newspaper=The Maui News|location=Wailuku|date=November 25, 1921|volume=|issue=|page=1|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82014689/1921-11-22/ed-1/seq-1/|accessdate=November 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220045942/http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82014689/1921-11-22/ed-1/seq-1/|archive-date=December 20, 2016|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref>

