'''Lara Roxx''' is the  [[Pseudonym|stage name]] of the [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[pornographic film actor|pornographic actress]] who, in March 2004, became the first of three known individuals in four years to contract [[HIV]] while making a U.S. [[pornographic film|pornographic video]].

==Career==
Roxx became famous in 2004 at age 21, after being exposed to [[HIV]] while doing a [[Pornography|pornographic]] scene with [[Darren James]]. She allegedly contracted the disease just two months after doing her first scene, a [[double anal]].<ref name=burnett>{{cite news | url=http://blogs.montrealgazette.com/2013/01/25/inside-lara-roxx-former-montreal-adult-film-star-on-the-deadly-price-of-porn-fame/ | title=Inside Lara Roxx: former Montreal adult-film star on the deadly price of porn fame | work=[[The Gazette (Montreal)|Montreal Gazette]] | date=January 25, 2013 | accessdate=January 26, 2013 | author=Burnett, Richard | authorlink=Richard Burnett}}</ref> Roxx said previously that she relied on the industry's HIV standards to ensure her safety.<ref name=cleanest>{{cite web|url=http://business.avn.com/articles/15762.html |title=Lara Roxx: "I thought porn people were the cleanest people in the world." |work=[[AVN (magazine)|Adult Video News]] |date=2004-04-17 |accessdate=2009-02-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510090658/http://business.avn.com/articles/15762.html |archivedate=2009-05-10 |df= }}</ref>

James and Roxx have been banned from any further porn production in the US. At the end of April 2004, it was confirmed that Jessica Dee and Miss Arroyo, after having worked with James, also tested positive for HIV.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.avn.com/articles/15987.html|title=Another First-Gen Woman Diagnosed as HIV-Positive|work=[[AVN (magazine)|Adult Video News]]|date=2004-05-05|accessdate=2009-02-08|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090821144824/http://business.avn.com/articles/15987.html|archivedate=2009-08-21|df=}}</ref>

Roxx, upon learning about James' being HIV-positive, said, "It totally made me realize how I trusted this system that wasn't to be trusted at all, because it obviously doesn't work," and "I thought porn people were the cleanest people in the world."<ref name=cleanest/>

She is the subject of the Canadian documentary film ''[[Inside Lara Roxx]]'', directed by Canadian filmmaker and photographer [[Mia Donovan]], which explores Roxx's 2004 [[HIV/AIDS|HIV infection]] and her life since the media coverage of this incident subsided.<ref name=burnett/><ref>{{cite web |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=May 2011 |title=Inside Lara Roxx |url=http://www.hotdocs.ca/film/title/inside_lara_roxx |website=hotdocs.ca |publisher=Hot Docs Canadian International Documentary Festival |accessdate= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207162454/http://www.hotdocs.ca/film/title/inside_lara_roxx |archivedate=2012-02-07 |df= }}</ref>

